"""
# CSS `:has()` Selector — Can I Use Summary

The URL `https://caniuse.com/css-has` is the **Can I Use** support table page for the **CSS `:has()` selector**, sometimes called the "parent selector."

## What is `:has()`?

The `:has()` pseudo-class is a CSS relational selector defined in the **CSS Selectors Level 4** specification. It allows you to select an element based on whether it contains (or is related to) certain descendants or siblings. For example:

```css
/* Select any <div> that contains a <p> */
div:has(p) {
  border: 1px solid red;
}

/* Select a <label> that has a following invalid input sibling */
label:has(+ input:invalid) {
  color: red;
}
```

This effectively gives CSS a "parent selector" — something developers requested for many years.

## Browser Support (Key Facts)

As of the latest data I have (up to early 2024):

| Browser | Supported Since |
|---|---|
| **Safari** | 15.4 (March 2022) — first browser to ship it |
| **Chrome** | 105 (August 2022) |
| **Edge** | 105 (August 2022, Chromium-based) |
| **Firefox** | 121 (December 2023) |
| **Opera** | 91 |
| **Chrome Android** | 105 |
| **Safari iOS** | 15.4 |
| **Samsung Internet** | 20.0 |

- **IE** — Not supported (and never will be, as IE is discontinued).
- **Opera Mini** — Not supported.

## Overall Support

By early 2024, `:has()` has broad support across all major evergreen browsers, covering roughly **~90%+** of global users. Firefox was the last major holdout and added support in version 121 (stable December 2023).

## Key Notes from the Page

- `:has()` **cannot** be used inside `querySelector()`/`querySelectorAll()` in some earlier implementations but now generally works in JS APIs as well.
- The spec originally labeled `:has()` as potentially limited to the "dynamic profile" (i.e., JavaScript only, not stylesheets), but browsers implemented it for CSS stylesheets too.
- Performance was a major concern (since it essentially requires ancestor/upward traversal), but browser engines implemented it with acceptable performance characteristics.
- **Forgiving selector list**: `:has()` uses a forgiving selector list, meaning if one argument is invalid, the others still work (consistent with `:is()` and `:where()`).

## Example Usage

```css
/* Style a card only if it contains an image */
.card:has(img) {
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr;
}

/* Style a form group when its input is focused */
.form-group:has(input:focus) {
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px blue;
}

/* Select an h1 that is immediately followed by a subtitle */
h1:has(+ .subtitle) {
  margin-bottom: 0;
}
```

This is one of the most significant CSS features added in recent years, finally enabling styling patterns that previously required JavaScript.
