# Cross-Document (Multi-Page) View Transitions

Cross-document view transitions (MPA View Transitions) allow smooth transitions between different pages without JavaScript frameworks. Here's how to implement them:

## CSS

Both the **source** and **destination** pages need the `@view-transition` at-rule:

```css
/* Include this on BOTH pages (source and destination) */

@view-transition {
  navigation: auto;
}
```

This opts the page into cross-document view transitions for same-origin navigations.

## Full Example

### Page 1 (`page1.html`)

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Page 1</title>
  <style>
    @view-transition {
      navigation: auto;
    }

    /* Default cross-fade applies automatically, but you can customize: */
    ::view-transition-old(root) {
      animation: fade-out 0.3s ease-in-out;
    }

    ::view-transition-new(root) {
      animation: fade-in 0.3s ease-in-out;
    }

    @keyframes fade-out {
      from { opacity: 1; }
      to { opacity: 0; }
    }

    @keyframes fade-in {
      from { opacity: 0; }
      to { opacity: 1; }
    }

    /* Give specific elements a view-transition-name to animate them independently */
    .hero-image {
      view-transition-name: hero;
    }

    h1 {
      view-transition-name: title;
    }

    body {
      font-family: sans-serif;
      margin: 2rem;
    }
  </style>
</head>
