## How It Works

1. **`document.startViewTransition(callback)`** — You pass a callback that performs the DOM mutation. The browser:
   - Captures a screenshot of the old state (`::view-transition-old`)
   - Runs your callback to update the DOM
   - Captures a screenshot of the new state (`::view-transition-new`)
   - Animates between the two using CSS animations on the pseudo-elements

2. **`::view-transition-old(root)` / `::view-transition-new(root)`** — These pseudo-elements represent the old and new states of the entire page (or named elements). You style them with standard CSS animations.

3. **`view-transition-name`** — Assign this CSS property to specific elements to give them their own independent transition (rather than being part of the `root` group). Each name must be unique on the page at the time of the transition.

4. **The returned `ViewTransition` object** has three promises:
   - **`updateCallbackDone`** — resolves when your DOM update callback finishes
   - **`ready`** — resolves when the pseudo-element tree is created and animation is about to start
   - **`finished`** — resolves when the transition animation completes and the new view is fully visible

> **Note:** This API is supported in Chromium-based browsers (Chrome 111+, Edge 111+). Firefox and Safari have been adding support. Always use feature detection (`if (document.startViewTransition)`).
