"""
Here's working JavaScript that uses `document.startViewTransition()` to animate a DOM update, with a fallback for unsupported browsers.

## HTML

```html
<main>
  <section></section>
  <button id="change-color">Change color</button>
</main>
```

## CSS

```css
html {
  --bg: indigo;
}

main {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 5px;
}

section {
  background-color: var(--bg);
  height: 60px;
  border-radius: 5px;
}

/* Control the transition timing via the view transition pseudo-element */
::view-transition-group(root) {
  animation-duration: 2s;
}
```

## JavaScript

```js
const colors = ["darkred", "darkslateblue", "darkgreen"];
const colBlock = document.querySelector("section");
let count = 0;

// The DOM mutation we want to animate.
const updateColor = () => {
  colBlock.style = `--bg: ${colors[count]}`;
  count = count !== colors.length - 1 ? ++count : 0;
};

const changeColor = () => {
  // Fallback for browsers that don't support View Transitions:
  if (!document.startViewTransition) {
    updateColor();
    return;
  }

  // With View Transitions:
  const transition = document.startViewTransition(() => {
    updateColor();
  });

  // ViewTransition exposes promises you can hook into:
  // transition.ready          -> pseudo-element tree created, animations about to start
  // transition.updateCallbackDone -> the updateCallback's promise has settled
  // transition.finished       -> all animations finished, new state visible
  transition.finished.then(() => {
    console.log("View transition complete");
  });
};

const changeColorButton = document.querySelector("#change-color");
changeColorButton.addEventListener("click", changeColor);
changeColorButton.addEventListener("keypress", changeColor);
```

## Notes on the real API

- **`document.startViewTransition(updateCallback)`** takes an optional callback that performs the DOM update. It returns a **`ViewTransition`** object. The API snapshots the current page, runs your callback, then animates from the old snapshot to the new state in the next frame.

- You can also call it with an options object: `document.startViewTransition({ update: updateCallback, types: ["slide-in"] })`. The `types` array applies view transition types, which you can target with the `:active-view-transition-type()` pseudo-class.

- The `updateCallback` may return a `Promise`. The transition begins once that promise fulfills; if it rejects, the transition is abandoned.

- The returned `ViewTransition` object has these members (per the spec):
  - `transition.updateCallbackDone` — promise that settles when the update callback finishes.
  - `transition.ready` — promise that fulfills once the pseudo-elements are created and animations are about to start (rejects if the transition can't begin).
  - `transition.finished` — promise that fulfills when the transition animation completes.
  - `transition.skipTransition()` — skips the animation (jumps to the end state).

- Animations are driven by CSS via pseudo-elements such as `::view-transition`, `::view-transition-group(root)`, `::view-transition-image-pair(root)`, `::view-transition-old(root)`, and `::view-transition-new(root)`. The example above customizes `animation-duration` on the `root` group.

- The feature reached **Baseline (Newly available)** status in October 2025; older browsers won't have `document.startViewTransition`, hence the feature-detection fallback.
"""

