"""
# View Transitions API Example

Here's working JavaScript using `document.startViewTransition()` to animate a DOM update.

## Basic Example

```javascript
function updateDOM() {
  // The actual DOM mutation happens here
  document.querySelector('#content').textContent = 'Updated content!';
  document.querySelector('#box').classList.toggle('active');
}

// Feature detection — startViewTransition may not exist
if (document.startViewTransition) {
  document.startViewTransition(() => updateDOM());
} else {
  // Fallback: update without animation
  updateDOM();
}
```

## With the returned ViewTransition object

`document.startViewTransition()` returns a `ViewTransition` object exposing three promises: `ready`, `updateCallbackDone`, and `finished`.

```javascript
function swapItems() {
  const list = document.querySelector('#list');
  // reverse the children
  const items = [...list.children];
  items.reverse().forEach(item => list.appendChild(item));
}

async function handleClick() {
  if (!document.startViewTransition) {
    swapItems();
    return;
  }

  const transition = document.startViewTransition(() => swapItems());

  // Resolves when pseudo-element tree is built and animation is about to start
  await transition.ready;
  console.log('Transition pseudo-elements ready');

  // Resolves when the DOM-updating callback has finished
  await transition.updateCallbackDone;

  // Resolves when the animation finishes (or rejects if skipped/failed)
  try {
    await transition.finished;
    console.log('Transition finished');
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Transition failed:', err);
  }
}

document.querySelector('#btn').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
```

## Async DOM update callback

The callback passed to `startViewTransition()` may return a Promise; the transition waits for it before capturing the new state.

```javascript
document.startViewTransition(async () => {
  const res = await fetch('/api/data');
  const data = await res.json();
  document.querySelector('#content').innerHTML = data.html;
});
```

## Skipping a transition

```javascript
const transition = document.startViewTransition(() => updateDOM());
// Immediately finishes the transition, skipping animation
transition.skipTransition();
```

## Required CSS for custom animations

The API snapshots elements into `::view-transition-*` pseudo-elements. Use `view-transition-name` to animate specific elements independently.

```css
/* Customize the default cross-fade duration */
::view-transition-old(root),
::view-transition-new(root) {
  animation-duration: 0.5s;
}

/* Give an element its own named transition */
#box {
  view-transition-name: box;
}

/* Custom keyframes for the named element */
::view-transition-old(box) {
  animation: 0.4s ease-out both fade-out;
}
::view-transition-new(box) {
  animation: 0.4s ease-in both fade-in;
}

@keyframes fade-out { to { opacity: 0; } }
@keyframes fade-in  { from { opacity: 0; } }
```

## Notes on real API surface

- **Method:** `document.startViewTransition(updateCallback)` — `updateCallback` is optional.
- **Returns:** a `ViewTransition` object with:
  - `ViewTransition.ready` (Promise)
  - `ViewTransition.updateCallbackDone` (Promise)
  - `ViewTransition.finished` (Promise)
  - `ViewTransition.skipTransition()` (method)
- **CSS property:** `view-transition-name`
- **Pseudo-elements:** `::view-transition`, `::view-transition-group()`, `::view-transition-image-pair()`, `::view-transition-old()`, `::view-transition-new()`
- **Browser support:** This is the **same-document** View Transitions API. As of my knowledge, it's supported in Chromium-based browsers (Chrome/Edge 111+). Firefox and Safari support has been progressing more recently — verify current support on MDN / caniuse before relying on it, hence the `if (document.startViewTransition)` feature check.

There is also a separate **cross-document** variant (for MPA navigations) configured via the CSS `@view-transition { navigation: auto; }` at-rule, which does not use `document.startViewTransition()`.
"""

