"""
Here is the JavaScript and CSS needed to implement an element-scoped View Transition. 

By calling `startViewTransition()` directly on a specific DOM element rather than the `document`, you restrict the view transition (and its visual overlay) to just that component's subtree. 

### HTML
```html
<button id="update-btn">Reverse List</button>

<!-- This is the component we will scope the view transition to -->
<ul id="my-list">
  <li id="item-1">Apple</li>
  <li id="item-2">Banana</li>
  <li id="item-3">Cherry</li>
</ul>
```

### CSS
To make the elements animate during the view transition, they must be assigned a unique `view-transition-name`. 

*Note: As of Chrome 147, the scope root (`#my-list`) will automatically have `contain: layout` and `view-transition-scope: all` applied to it during the transition.*

```css
/* Give each item a unique view-transition-name so the browser can track their positions */
#item-1 {
  view-transition-name: list-item-1;
}
#item-2 {
  view-transition-name: list-item-2;
}
#item-3 {
  view-transition-name: list-item-3;
}

ul {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 8px;
  width: 200px;
}

li {
  padding: 8px;
  background: #f0f0f0;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  list-style: none;
}
```

### JavaScript
Call `Element.startViewTransition()` on the target element (`#my-list`) instead of `document`. This ensures that other animations or interactive elements outside of `#my-list` are completely unaffected by the transition freeze.

```javascript
const listComponent = document.getElementById('my-list');
const updateBtn = document.getElementById('update-btn');

updateBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  // 1. Fallback for browsers that do not support element-scoped view transitions
  if (!listComponent.startViewTransition) {
    reverseList();
    return;
  }

  // 2. Start the element-scoped view transition
  listComponent.startViewTransition(() => {
    // This DOM mutation is captured and animated only within the listComponent
    reverseList();
  });
});

function reverseList() {
  // Simple DOM manipulation to reverse the order of the list items
  const items = Array.from(listComponent.children);
  items.reverse().forEach(item => listComponent.appendChild(item));
}
```
"""

